---------: cp, mv
Ex: copying file1 content to file2
 - touch file1 file2 
 - cat > file1
   hello world!
 - cp file1 file2
 - cp file1 /home/demo/user 
 - cp /home/demo/file.txt .
Ex: copying file1 content to dir directory. 
 - cp file1 dir
Ex: cp dir1 to dir2 directory
 - cp -r/-R dir1 dir2

mv: moving from source to destination, Renaming the file. 
 - mv text.pdf home/ : moving text.pdf to home directory. 
 - mv home/ homenew/ :renaming a directory home to homenew

---------------------: find, grep, sort :-----------------------
find: to search the file or directory path.
Ex:
 - find / -name <file1> : to search in entire system
 - find 

grep: search for the string/word in a text file.
Ex:
 - grep -i <error> file1 , i for case sensitive.
 - grep -n <error> file1, matching string along with line number. 

sort: to sort the results of a search either alphabetically / numerically.
 - sort file1.txt - returns them in a alphabetical order
 - sort -r file1.txt - returns in a reverse order.
 - sort -f file1.txt - case insensitive sorting
 - sort -n file1.txt - returns the result as per numerical order 


-----------------------: sed, awk :-------------------------
sed: stream editor (search a word in the file & replace with the new word)
Note:
 - it'll only modify the o/p, but there will be no change in the original file. 
Ex:
 - sed 's/old_test/new_text/' <file_name> , original file not change. only give o/p.    
 - sed -i 's/old_test/new_text/' <file_name> , going to update the file
 - sed 's/old_test/new_text/g' <file_name>  , g:globally
 - sed -n '5,10p' <file_name> , display 5 to 10 lines. 
 

