==============================:Linux Networking Commands :========================================================
1. Ping (Packet Internet Groper)
 - Whether the ip address or name is pingable or not. (whether connected or not)
 - ttl(time-to-live) --> network connection with the particular host.
 - ttl is a value for the period of time that a packet, or data, should exist on a computer or network before being discarded.
Ex:
# ping google.com
# ping -c 5 google.com
o/p:
 PING google.com (142.251.163.102) 56(84) bytes of data.
 64 bytes from wv-in-f102.1e100.net (142.251.163.102): icmp_seq=1 ttl=50 time=2.07 ms
 64 bytes from wv-in-f102.1e100.net (142.251.163.102): icmp_seq=2 ttl=50 time=2.22 ms
 --- google.com ping statistics ---
 34 packets transmitted, 34 received, 0% packet loss, time 33038ms

2. netstat:
 - Showing established connection 
 - shows <ip address> and <dns> name & the status of ports.
 - shows connection type like ssh, http, https etc.
O/p:
 Active Internet connections (w/o servers)
 Proto  Recv-Q  Send-Q  Local Address           Foreign Address          State      
 tcp        0    200   ip-172-31-92-133.ec:ssh  ec2-18-206-107-27:57520  ESTABLISHED

3. arp -a
 - Use to check ip and mac address. 
o/p:
 Address                  HWtype  HWaddress           Flags Mask            Iface
 instance-data.ec2.inter  ether   12:68:96:b6:50:ef   C                     eth0
 ip-172-31-80-1.ec2.inte  ether   12:68:96:b6:50:ef   C                     eth0

4. nslookup:
- To find dns server for a domain./ dns details.
- like name, address.
O/p:
 Server:         172.31.0.2
 Address:        172.31.0.2#53

 Non-authoritative answer:
 Name:   google.com
 Address: 142.251.111.113

5. traceroute:
